soc.message

Class SOCGameState

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.message.SOCMessage
      • soc.message.SOCGameState
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, SOCMessageForGame

    public class SOCGameState
extends SOCMessage
implements SOCMessageForGame
    This message communicates the current state of the game.

    For some states, such as GameState.WAITING_FOR_ROB_CHOOSE_PLAYER, another message (such as SOCChoosePlayerRequest) will follow to prompt the current player. For others, such as GameState.WAITING_FOR_DISCOVERY or GameState.WAITING_FOR_ROBBER_OR_PIRATE, sending this SOCGameState message implies that the player must decide and respond. See the state list below for details.

    When a new game is starting (leaving state NEW_GAME), the server sends the new game state and then sends SOCStartGame.

    In v2.0.00 and newer, some messages contain an optional Game State field to change state as part of that message's change, instead of sending a separate SOCGameState: SOCStartGame, SOCTurn. Games with clients older than v2.0.00 are sent SOCGameState instead of using that field. To find uses of such messages, do a where-used search for VERSION_FOR_GAME_STATE_AS_FIELD.

    States sent by this message, and messages sent afterwards/client response expected:

    • NEW_GAME: -
    • READY: -
    • READY_RESET_WAIT_ROBOT_DISMISS: -
    • START1A: Current player: Place a settlement (all placement requests from clients are sent using SOCPutPiece)
    • START1B: Current player: Place a road
    • START2A: Current player: Place a settlement
    • START2B: Current player: Place a road
    • START3A: Current player: Place a settlement
    • START3B: Current player: Place a road
    • STARTS_WAITING_FOR_PICK_GOLD_RESOURCE: Server sends game a "x, y, and z need to pick resources from the gold hex" prompt text. Sends the game SOCPlayerElement(NUM_PICK_GOLD_HEX_RESOURCES). Sends specific player(s) SOCSimpleRequest(PROMPT_PICK_RESOURCES).
    • ROLL_OR_CARD: Server sends game SOCRollDicePrompt with current player number. Current player: Send SOCRollDice or SOCPlayDevCardRequest
    • PLAY1: Current player: Build, play and buy cards, trade, etc. When done with turn, send SOCEndTurn
    • PLACING_ROAD: Current player: Place a road
    • PLACING_SETTLEMENT: Current player: Place a settlement
    • PLACING_CITY: Current player: Place a city
    • PLACING_ROBBER: Current player: Choose a new robber hex and send SOCMoveRobber
    • PLACING_PIRATE: Current player: Choose a new pirate hex and send SOCMoveRobber
    • PLACING_SHIP: Current player: Place a ship
    • PLACING_FREE_ROAD1: Current player: Place a road
    • PLACING_FREE_ROAD2: Current player: Place a road
    • PLACING_INV_ITEM: Current player: Place the previously-designated SOCInventoryItem. Their placement message to server depends on the scenario and item type, documented at SOCInventoryItemAction. For example, in scenario SC_FTRI the player sends a SOCSimpleRequest(TRADE_PORT_PLACE) with the requested edge coordinate; the messages responding to that are documented at SOCSimpleRequest.TRADE_PORT_PLACE.
      Placement of some item types can sometimes be cancelled by sending SOCCancelBuildRequest(INV_ITEM_PLACE_CANCEL) instead.
    • WAITING_FOR_DISCARDS: Server sends game a "x, y, and z need to discard" prompt text. Players who must discard are sent SOCDiscardRequest and must respond with SOCDiscard. After each client response, if still waiting for other players to discard, server sends game another prompt text. Otherwise sends game its new SOCGameState
    • WAITING_FOR_ROB_CHOOSE_PLAYER: Server sends current player SOCChoosePlayerRequest listing possible victims. Current player: Choose a victim to rob, send SOCChoosePlayer
    • WAITING_FOR_DISCOVERY: Current player: Choose 2 resources and send SOCPickResources
    • WAITING_FOR_MONOPOLY: Current player: Choose a resource type and send SOCPickResourceType
    • WAITING_FOR_ROBBER_OR_PIRATE: Current player: Choose whether to move the Robber or the Pirate, send SOCChoosePlayer(CHOICE_MOVE_ROBBER or CHOICE_MOVE_PIRATE)
    • WAITING_FOR_ROB_CLOTH_OR_RESOURCE: Current player: Choose a victim to rob and whether to take a resource or cloth, send SOCChoosePlayer. See that message's javadoc for how to encode both choices
    • WAITING_FOR_PICK_GOLD_RESOURCE: Same message flow as WAITING_FOR_DISCARDS: Server sends game a "x, y, and z need to pick resources from the gold hex" prompt text. For each player who must pick, the game is sent SOCPlayerElement(NUM_PICK_GOLD_HEX_RESOURCES) and the player is sent SOCSimpleRequest(PROMPT_PICK_RESOURCES). They must choose resource(s) and send SOCPickResources. After each client response, server sends game its SOCGameState; if multiple players had to pick, that state is still WAITING_FOR_PICK_GOLD_RESOURCE and another "need to pick" prompt text is also sent.
    • SPECIAL_BUILDING: Current player: Build, buy cards, etc. When done, send SOCEndTurn
    • LOADING: -
    • LOADING_RESUMING: -
    • GAME_OVER: Server announces the winner with SOCGameElements(CURRENT_PLAYER), and sends text messages reporting winner's name, final score, each player's victory-point cards, game length, and a SOCGameStats. Each player is sent text with their resource roll totals. win-loss count for this session, and how long they've been connected.
    This list doesn't mention some informational/cosmetic text messages, such as the START1A prompt "It's Joe's turn to build a settlement" or PLACING_ROBBER's "Lily will move the robber".
    Author:
    Robert S Thomas <thomas@infolab.northwestern.edu>

    • Method Detail

      • getGame

        public java.lang.String getGame()
        Description copied from interface: SOCMessageForGame
        Name of game this message is for, if any. Must not be null in a message sent to the server: If message is not about per-game structures or code, use SOCMessage.GAME_NONE.

        At the server, the message treater dispatches incoming SOCMessageForGames based on their getGame():

        • null: Message is ignored
        • SOCMessage.GAME_NONE: Message is handled by SOCServer itself or SOCServerMessageHandler
        • Any other game name: Looks for a game with that name, to dispatch to the GameHandler for that game's type. If no game with that name is found, the message is ignored.
        Specified by:
        getGame in interface SOCMessageForGame
        Returns:
        the game name

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Description copied from class: SOCMessage
        Simple human-readable delimited representation, used for debug purposes: SOCPutPiece:game=test5|playerNumber=3|pieceType=0|coord=40a
        Could also be used by a SOCServer.recordGameEvent(String, SOCMessage) implementation.

        Within this representation, message parameters should be in same order used by SOCMessage.toCmd() and parseDataStr(..). Should be parseable by SOCMessage.parseMsgStr(String) which calls SOCMessage.stripAttribNames(String), which your class can override if needed.

        Specified by:
        toString in class SOCMessage
        Returns:
        a human readable form of the message

        SOCMessage.toCmd()
